{"title_page": "Louise A. Smith", "text_new": "{{other people|Louise Smith}}\n{{short description|American author}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Louise A. Smith\n| education   = [[Stanford University]], [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n| occupation  = writer, editor\n}}\n\n'''Louise A. Smith''' is an author best known for her biography of [[Mary Baker Eddy]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nSmith grew up in [[Baldwin Hills, California]]. She was heavily involved in sports despite many girls at the time not playing, and received numerous recognitions including Player of the Year and MVP during her high school years.<ref name=\"bevhills\">{{cite web |title=Beverly Hills Athletes Inducted Into Hall of Fame |url=http://bvh.stparchive.com/Archive/BVH/BVH11032011p08.php |publisher=Beverly Hills Weekly |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> She then earned a scholarship to [[Stanford University]] and was the 1981 Stanford MVP, and helped the team win its first NCAA women's basketball tournament.<ref name=\"bevhills\"/> After graduating she decided to be a writer, and supported her career by couching basketball. She then got her MFA in writing at [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in New York, where she worked as a writer, editor, and medical proofreader for over 20 years.<ref name=\"bevhills\"/><ref name=\"Sandoz\">{{cite book |last1=Sandoz |first1=Joli |last2=Winans |first2=Joby |title=Whatever It Takes: Women on Women's Sport |date=1999 |publisher=Macmillan |page=316 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kBA4WvUxRiMC}}</ref>\n\n==Mary Baker Eddy biography==\n\nSmith wrote ''Mary Baker Eddy: Founder'' as part of [[Infobase Publishing|Chelsea House Publishers']] series on \"American Women of Achievement\" in 1991. It was reviewed as creating \"a balanced portrait of the religious leader, allowing readers to decide for themselves about Eddy's spirituality and her contributions.\"<ref name=\"kirkus\">{{cite web |title=Mary Baker Eddy |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/louise-a-smith/mary-baker-eddy-2/ |website=Kirkus Reviews |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The book attracted the attention of [[The First Church of Christ, Scientist]], and they received rights to publish it under the name ''Mary Baker Eddy: Discoverer and Founder of Christian Science'' with added material as part of their \"Twentieth-Century Biographers\" Series on [[Mary Baker Eddy]] in 1992, and has been published by them and sold in [[Christian Science Reading Room]]s since that time. Smith especially relied on the biographies of [[Robert Peel (Christian Science)|Robert Peel]] and Jewel Spangler Smaus for her book.<ref name=\"mbel\">{{cite web |title=Timeline: Biographies of Mary Baker Eddy |url=https://www.marybakereddylibrary.org/research/timeline-for-biographies-of-mary-baker-eddy/ |publisher=Mary Baker Eddy Library |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The book is popular for providing a concise and easy to read the history of Eddy's life.\n\n==Published books==\n\n* ''Mary Baker Eddy: Founder'' (1991) Chelsea House Publishers.\n* ''Fear of the Black Rose'' (2007) AuthorHouse.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:Beverly Hills High School alumni]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:People from Baldwin Hills, Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author}}\n{{other people|Louise Smith}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Louise A. Smith\n| education   = [[Stanford University]], [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n| occupation  = writer, editor\n}}\n\n'''Louise A. Smith''' is an author best known for her biography of [[Mary Baker Eddy]].\n\n==Early Life==\n\nSmith grew up in [[Baldwin Hills, California]]. She was heavily involved in sports despite many girls at the time not playing, and received numerous recognitions including Player of the Year and MVP during her high school years.<ref name=\"bevhills\">{{cite web |title=Beverly Hills Athletes Inducted Into Hall of Fame |url=http://bvh.stparchive.com/Archive/BVH/BVH11032011p08.php |publisher=Beverly Hills Weekly |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> She then earned a scholarship to [[Stanford University]] and was the 1981 Stanford MVP, and helped the team win its first NCAA women's basketball tournament.<ref name=\"bevhills\"/> After graduating she decided to be a writer, and supported her career by couching basketball. She then got her MFA in writing at [[Sarah Lawrence College]] in New York, where she worked as a writer, editor, and medical proofreader for over 20 years.<ref name=\"bevhills\"/><ref name=\"Sandoz\">{{cite book |last1=Sandoz |first1=Joli |last2=Winans |first2=Joby |title=Whatever It Takes: Women on Women's Sport |date=1999 |publisher=Macmillan |page=316 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kBA4WvUxRiMC}}</ref>\n\n==Mary Baker Eddy biography==\n\nSmith wrote ''Mary Baker Eddy: Founder'' as part of [[Infobase Publishing|Chelsea House Publishers']] series on \"American Women of Achievement\" in 1991. It was reviewed as creating \"a balanced portrait of the religious leader, allowing readers to decide for themselves about Eddy's spirituality and her contributions.\"<ref name=\"kirkus\">{{cite web |title=Mary Baker Eddy |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/louise-a-smith/mary-baker-eddy-2/ |website=Kirkus Reviews |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The book attracted the attention of [[The First Church of Christ, Scientist]], and they received rights to publish it under the name ''Mary Baker Eddy: Discoverer and Founder of Christian Science'' with added material as part of their \"Twentieth-Century Biographers\" Series on [[Mary Baker Eddy]] in 1992, and has been published by them and sold in [[Christian Science Reading Room]]s since that time. Smith especially relied on the biographies of [[Robert Peel (Christian Science)|Robert Peel]] and Jewel Spangler Smaus for her book.<ref name=\"mbel\">{{cite web |title=Timeline: Biographies of Mary Baker Eddy |url=https://www.marybakereddylibrary.org/research/timeline-for-biographies-of-mary-baker-eddy/ |publisher=Mary Baker Eddy Library |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The book is popular for providing a concise and easy to read the history of Eddy's life.\n\n==Published books==\n\n* ''Mary Baker Eddy: Founder'' (1991) Chelsea House Publishers.\n* ''Fear of the Black Rose'' (2007) AuthorHouse.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:Beverly Hills High School alumni]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:People from Baldwin Hills, Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louise_A._Smith"}
